# Re-Imagined Strategy Report: Order Intake

## 1) Executive Summary — One Big Move

One Big Move: Establish a Clean Core Zero-Touch Order Intake Fabric—standardize decision gates in SAP S/4HANA (ATP, price/credit/delivery gating), orchestrate all intake and exception resolution in a Side-Car on SAP BTP, and deploy targeted SAP Joule/GenAI agents to convert unstructured email/WhatsApp/fax into structured orders and change requests—so that 90%+ of orders flow from intent to acknowledgement without human touches while preserving auditable controls.

Why now: The current global Order Intake exhibits high manual variance, brittle file-drop automations, and control gaps (no ATP; no price validation at entry; off-time import batches; manual IDoc triage; dual-system exceptions). These materially increase cycle time and risk across regions (e.g., ANZ ATP gap; GB pricing checks; EMENA custom ZVA05N; Mexico/Brazil/Uruguay/Argentina reliance on WhatsApp/Gmail; China Digital Hub double-entry; India DC-based entry). {DOC1, Multiple regional sections, “ATP functionality gap (currently no ATP)… no price validation at entry… off time import… failed IDoc monitored in WE05… Digital Hub mandatory… DC-based manual entry… WhatsApp/email reliance,” paraphrase}

How:  
- Path A (Foundation): S/4HANA standardization to re-introduce entry controls and eliminate custom/legacy dependence (implement core ATP/MOQ gating; pricing/incompletion checks at entry; refine credit/delivery blocks; retire Z-customs like ZVA05N; normalize EDI entry; align proforma invoicing via standard output). {DOC1, APAC-ANZ/GB/EMENA/China sections, “ATP gap… no price validation at entry… ZVA05N only in EMENA… ZF delivery block preferred… VA01 not used for EDI entry,” paraphrase}
- Path B (Bridge): SAP BTP Side-Car orchestrates deterministic channel normalization, exception handling, acknowledgements, duplicate/hold/cancel logic, mobile/portal integrations, batch-to-near-real-time shifts, and event-driven monitoring—explicitly keeping all custom logic outside the ERP kernel. {DOC1, Multiple, “manual entry for exceptions/new SKUs… CSV shared folder automation… auto-cancellation Y1/Y5… failed IDocs WE05… off-time imports… Digital Hub mandatory… Vector EDI reconciliation,” paraphrase}
- Path C (Game Changer): SAP Joule/GenAI agents for unstructured channels (email/WhatsApp/fax), change-request comprehension, export-compliance summarization, and deduction triage—operationalized safely via Shadow → Co-Pilot → Autopilot with audit trails and measurable precision thresholds. {DOC1, Mexico/Brazil/Uruguay/Argentina/JKSEAT/SA sections, “heavy reliance on Gmail… WhatsApp/email for error resolution… fax/website orders manually entered… direct network via email,” paraphrase; DOC2, “Email-based order changes/triage in flow,” paraphrase}

Clean Core enforcement: All custom routing, exception logic, and unstructured perception reside in the BTP Side-Car and SAP Joule agents—never embedded in S/4HANA. The ERP remains the system of record and configuration center for standard gating and controls.

Expected outcome:  
- Eliminate re-keying and manual triage touchpoints for predominant volumes while strengthening first-time-right controls (ATP, pricing, credit/delivery gating).  
- Achieve consistent customer acknowledgement within minutes, not batch windows.  
- Reduce IDoc failure backlogs through event-driven orchestration and automated resolution workflows.  
- Convert unstructured communications into auditable transactions with human-in-the-loop oversight during the Shadow/Co-Pilot phases.

## 2) Current Reality Synthesis

Global intake is fragmented by region, channel, and tooling, creating a patchwork of manual and brittle automations:

- Manual exception entry is pervasive when EDI/Esker/CSV automations break (e.g., new SKUs, data sync failures) and across exports/smaller segments. {DOC1, NA/CALATIN sections, “Manual entry and intervention… exceptions/new SKUs/data sync failures… exports and smaller segments,” paraphrase}
- Entry controls are weak or absent in multiple regions—no ATP (ANZ), no entry price validation (GB), and custom holds (Z7) driving manual review queues. {DOC1, APAC-ANZ/GB sections, “ATP functionality gap… EDI orders only basic sense checks… Z7 CSR hold universal application,” paraphrase}
- Reliance on unstructured channels is significant—Gmail/WhatsApp dominate several regions, fax and websites in JKSEAT, email change requests globally. {DOC1, Mexico/Brazil/Uruguay/Argentina/JKSEAT; DOC2, “Email-based change requests,” paraphrase}
- Integration patterns are inconsistent and brittle—CSV file drops to shared folders with macros/watcher processes; Excel macros for end-of-day confirmations; region-specific Z-transactions (ZVA05N). {DOC1, JKSEAT/ANZ/EMENA sections, “CSV files uploaded to shared folder… macro… Excel macros EOD… ZVA05N import,” paraphrase}
- Orchestration and monitoring are manual—off-time import batches in EMENA; manual WE05 IDoc monitoring and EDI failure triage. {DOC1, EMENA/GB global sections, “orders imported during off time… if error in EDI generates failed IDoc… viewed in WE05,” paraphrase}
- China mandates a Digital Hub gateway with manual entry prior to EDI posting; India uses DC-based manual entry for non-EDI orders. {DOC1, China/India sections, “Orders manually entered into Digital Hub before EDI… DC staff manually enter non-EDI orders,” paraphrase}

These patterns drive rework loops, inconsistent customer experience, and compliance risks (e.g., export documentation, FSSAI validation) due to missing or late checks. {DOC1, CALATIN/India, “Exports require extra documentation… FSSAI license validation at order creation,” paraphrase}

Hotspots (Top 5 Item_IDs)
1. P-027 — No ATP capability (ANZ): High risk of accepting orders without availability; downstream rework. {DOC1, APAC-ANZ section, “ATP functionality gap (currently no ATP)”}  
2. P-043 — No price validation at entry for EDI orders (GB): Leads to downstream pricing claims and disputes. {DOC1, GB section, “EDI orders undergo only basic sense checks; no comprehensive price validation at entry”}  
3. P-028 — Mandatory manual entry into Digital Hub (China): Double entry/rekeying increases effort and error risk. {DOC1, APAC-CHINA section, “Orders are manually entered into the Digital Hub… before triggering sales orders into SAP via EDI”}  
4. P-046 — Manual monitoring of failed IDocs (GB): Error handling via WE05 creates backlog risk. {DOC1, GB section, “if there is an error in the EDI it will generate a failed idoc which can be viewed in WE05”}  
5. P-001 — Manual entry for exceptions/new SKUs/data sync failures (NA): Frequent exception path, breaks automation and introduces delays. {DOC1, NA section, “Manual entry and intervention are required for exceptions, new SKUs, or data sync failures”}

## 3) Strategy: Layered Re-Imagination using Path A/B/C

### Path A: SAP S/4HANA Core Standardization (Foundation)

Objective: Re-establish first-time-right controls in Clean Core S/4HANA through configuration and standard capabilities, eliminating custom transaction dependence and excessive manual holds.

Recommendations (Clean Core—configuration only; no custom code in ERP):

- Implement ATP and MOQ gating at order entry globally, prioritizing ANZ and JKSEAT:  
  - Address ANZ “no ATP” to prevent accepting unfulfillable orders. Extend to JKSEAT where orders are taken weeks/months ahead without local ATP/MOQ gating. {DOC1, APAC-ANZ, “ATP functionality gap (currently no ATP)” and APAC-JKSEAT, “No local ATP/MOQ gating; sourcing regions run ATP”}
- Enforce pricing validation at entry for both EDI and manual orders (GB baseline for global pattern):  
  - Configure SD pricing/incompletion controls to stop orders with pricing gaps before confirmation. {DOC1, GB, “EDI orders… no comprehensive price validation… Manual orders… no price check at entry; incompletion log identifies gaps”}
- Normalize EDI order entry to standard process (eliminate VA02/VA03 variance in ANZ):  
  - Ensure EDI posts via standard creation approach (e.g., VA01 process equivalent) rather than change/display transactions. {DOC1, APAC-ANZ, “VA01 is not used for EDI order entry. VA02 and VA03 is used”}
- Retire EMENA ZVA05N import transaction; replace with standard S/4HANA equivalent integration design:  
  - Remove region-specific custom reliance to simplify upgrade and support. {DOC1, EMENA, “ZVA05N import transaction… Only applicable to EMENA”}
- Replace universal Z7 CSR hold with standard gating and risk-based holds:  
  - Configure delivery/credit/ATP/incompletion gates to avoid catch-all manual review, reducing cycle time. {DOC1, APAC-ANZ, “Z7 CSR Hold Implementation: Universal application… enables manual review”}
- Align credit/delivery block policies using standard S/4 Credit Management and delivery blocks:  
  - Reduce reliance on blanket 100% credit blocks (India); apply targeted ZF delivery blocks as per China practice. {DOC1, India/China, “100% credit block by default… ZF delivery blocks preferred over credit blocks”}
- Standardize Proforma Invoice issuance in S/4 Output Management for special cases (Brazil CPU orders):  
  - Remove ECC-only VF01/VF02 dependence for proforma as a control document. {DOC1, Brazil, “Proforma invoices for CPU orders are issued via SAP ECC VF01/VF02”}
- Improve availability visibility vs MB5T manual checks (India):  
  - Use S/4HANA real-time availability/analytics to reduce manual MB5T reliance at intake gate. {DOC1, India, “MB5T used for stock in transit checks”}

Evidence for Path A necessity is pervasive: gaps in ATP (ANZ/JKSEAT), pricing checks (GB), and custom transactions/holds (EMENA ZVA05N, ANZ Z7) degrade control efficacy. {DOC1, Multiple regional sections, paraphrase}

Clean Core enforcement: All business rules beyond standard configuration (e.g., exception patterns) are implemented in BTP Side-Car—no custom code in the S/4 kernel.

### Path B: SAP BTP Platform Enhancements / Deterministic Automation (Bridge)

Objective: Orchestrate all intake channels and deterministic decisions in a Side-Car, consolidating monitoring, exception routing, and automation. This keeps custom logic out of the ERP while increasing process reliability and reducing manual touchpoints.

Recommendations (deterministic; Side-Car on SAP BTP):

- Channel normalization and replacement of brittle CSV/macro automations:  
  - Replace shared-folder CSV pickers/macros with managed integrations and validations (JKSEAT, NA, Italy). {DOC1, JKSEAT/NA/EMENA, “CSV files uploaded to shared folder… macro… CSV process (Italy) via EDI… CSV unique to NA,” paraphrase}
- Export and compliance workflow automation:  
  - Deterministic rules for Incoterms/WH routing (NA exports), required documentation gating (CALATIN), and monthly export cycle orchestration (India). {DOC1, NA/CALATIN/India, “manual changes for export scenarios… exports require extra documentation… export orders processed in monthly cycles,” paraphrase}
- Exception routing for new SKUs/data sync failures:  
  - Auto-route exceptions from EDI/Esker/CSV to the right resolver queues with enriched context, and enable controlled replay after master-data fixes. {DOC1, NA global motif, “Manual entry and intervention… exceptions/new SKUs/data sync failures,” paraphrase}
- Event-driven IDoc/EDI monitoring and resolution workflow:  
  - Subscribe to post-processing events to alert/respond to WE05 failures with guided playbooks, reducing manual polling. {DOC1, GB/global, “failed idoc… viewed in WE05,” paraphrase}
- Duplicate detection and auto-cancel/merge logic for EDI and manual:  
  - Deterministic de-duplication (PO number/supplier/time heuristics) to prevent fulfilment errors. {DOC1, APAC-ANZ/GB, “Duplicate EDI order manual deletion required… duplicate POs auto-hold,” paraphrase}
- Auto-cancellation for unpaid orders (extend China’s logic globally where policy allows):  
  - Manage Y1/Y5 (or equivalent) reason codes in Side-Car with notifications to customers. {DOC1, APAC-CHINA, “Auto-cancellation… reason codes (Y1, Y5) for unpaid orders”}
- Acknowledgement consolidation and automation:  
  - Replace Excel macro EOD confirmations (ANZ) and manual email confirmations (GB; India limited auto-acks) with BTP-driven acknowledgements on order creation/acceptance. {DOC1, APAC-ANZ/GB/India, “End-of-day confirmations via Excel macros… Manual process only—no automatic customer notification… Only Reliance has automated acknowledgements,” paraphrase}
- Digital Hub (China) automation:  
  - Eliminate rekeying by integrating Hub-to-SAP via deterministic APIs, including resilience for the “single gateway” dependency and failover procedures. {DOC1, APAC-CHINA, “Orders manually entered into the Digital Hub… No Direct Customer EDI: all orders flow through Digital Hub,” paraphrase}
- Centralize India DC-based manual entry:  
  - Provide Side-Car forms/API endpoints for DCs to capture non-EDI orders centrally with validations before ERP posting. {DOC1, APAC-INDIA, “non-EDI orders… manually entered by distribution center staff; decentralized model,” paraphrase}
- Uruguay Power Street mobile order normalization:  
  - Normalize mobile payloads and “on-the-spot” truck orders with deterministic transforms prior to ERP posting. {DOC1, Uruguay, “Power Street… Orders are loaded on the spot (trucks),” paraphrase}
- Vector EDI reconciliation (SA):  
  - Implement next-day reconciliation workflow to pair indirect orders with SAP postings and flag gaps. {DOC1, SA, “Automated (Indirect Network via Vector EDI),” plus global motif on backward integration, paraphrase}
- Shift off-time batch imports (EMENA) to near-real-time:  
  - Replace off-time imports and ZVA05N dependency with event-driven integration for timely visibility/acks. {DOC1, EMENA, “Orders… imported during off time… ZVA05N import transaction only in EMENA,” paraphrase}

Clean Core enforcement: All routing, validations, and automations above are implemented in SAP BTP Side-Car; S/4HANA receives clean, compliant orders and updates through standard interfaces. No custom code in ERP. {DOC1, Global motif on manual exceptions and failures; Path B classifications}

### Path C: SAP Joule/GenAI Agentic AI Deployment (Game Changer)

Objective: Apply agentic AI only where unstructured inputs dominate and deterministic rules are insufficient—email/WhatsApp/fax/order-change comprehension and cross-system evidence synthesis—operationalized under strict governance.

Recommendations (agentic; SAP Joule/GenAI):

- Multi-Channel Communications Harvester (email/WhatsApp/fax/website captures):  
  - Parse intent and line-item details from Gmail/WhatsApp threads (Mexico, Brazil, Uruguay, Argentina), faxed POs and customer websites (JKSEAT), and retail/hardcopy orders (Argentina). Convert to structured orders with confidence scoring and human-in-loop approvals in Shadow/Co-Pilot phases. {DOC1, Mexico/Brazil/Uruguay/Argentina/JKSEAT/Argentina, “Gmail heavily used… WhatsApp/email… fax and website orders are manually entered… extensive manual review for retail/hardcopy,” paraphrase}
- Order Change Advisor:  
  - Read email-based change requests (global, ANZ), locate corresponding orders, propose safe changes (dates, quantities, ship-to) with policy checks (credit/ATP/price), and stage for approver release. {DOC1, APAC-ANZ, “All changes… processed manually in SAP based on email”; DOC2, Global intake, “Change Request handling via email,” paraphrase}
- Export & Compliance Copilot:  
  - Extract and validate export documentation, detect missing items, and summarize compliance status; propose ZF delivery block usage vs credit block per policy; integrate with BTP gating for release. {DOC1, CALATIN/China, “Exports require extra documentation… ZF delivery blocks preferred over credit blocks,” paraphrase}
- Deduction/Dispute Evidence Synthesizer:  
  - Aggregate evidence across channels and systems, match to orders/shipments, and prepare concise packets for dispute resolution to reduce cycle time. {DOC1, Global motif, “Deduction and dispute triage requires manual evidence reconciliation,” paraphrase}

Operational guardrails:  
- Agents must write decisions and extracted fields to the Side-Car with explainability, confidence scores, and full transcript/document links for audit; ERP updates only via deterministic APIs with human approval in Shadow/Co-Pilot. {Not specified in inputs—operational guardrail derived from Clean Core principle}

Clean Core enforcement: Agents do not execute custom logic inside ERP; they propose or submit via Side-Car APIs, which then invoke S/4 standard services.

Evidence: Unstructured communications and manual processing are pervasive—email/WhatsApp/fax orders, manual change requests, and export/deduction documentation—requiring perception that deterministic rules cannot provide. {DOC1, Mexico/Brazil/Uruguay/Argentina/JKSEAT/global; DOC2, intake flow with email-based changes, paraphrase}

## 4) Architecture of the Future State

Operating Model: Hub-and-Spoke

- Hub: SAP S/4HANA as the immutable System of Record, holding master data, pricing, credit, ATP, and order documents. All business-critical decisions codified via configuration (Path A). {DOC1, Multiple regional control gaps—addressed by S/4 configuration, paraphrase}
- Spokes:  
  - SAP BTP Side-Car as the deterministic orchestration plane—channel adapters, validations, exception routing, event-driven monitoring, acknowledgements, duplicate/cancel logic, and integrations (Digital Hub, Power Street, Vector, EDI, Esker, CSV retirement). {DOC1, NA/EMENA/JKSEAT/China/India/Uruguay/SA, “CSV/macros… Digital Hub… Power Street… Vector EDI… off-time import,” paraphrase}  
  - SAP Joule/GenAI agents attached to unstructured channels (email/WhatsApp/fax/websites) and change/complaint flows. Agents publish extracted data and proposed actions to the Side-Car for gating and ERP submission via standard APIs. {DOC1/DOC2, multiple references to unstructured channels and manual change processing, paraphrase}

Data Flow (illustrative):  
- Intake Channel → Side-Car Ingestion (deterministic) → Validations (pricing completeness, ATP call-outs, credit/delivery gating) → If unstructured: Joule agent extraction → Side-Car Business Rules → S/4 order creation/update → Acknowledgement triggered via Side-Car → Monitoring/Exception management. {DOC1, Global motifs on gating gaps and channel variance; DOC2, intake steps, paraphrase}

Agent Personas (minimum three; all operate via Side-Car; Autonomy phases follow Trust Gap Protocol)

1) Multi-Channel Comms Harvester (Agent)  
- Responsibilities: Ingest Gmail/Outlook and WhatsApp messages, fax PDFs, and website submissions; classify intent (new order vs inquiry vs change); extract customer, ship-to, material/SKU, quantities, dates, Incoterms; fill missing fields via Side-Car master-data lookups.  
- Inputs: Email threads, chat transcripts, fax PDFs/images, website exports. {DOC1, Mexico/Brazil/Uruguay/Argentina/JKSEAT, “Gmail/WhatsApp… fax/website orders… manual,” paraphrase}  
- Decisions: Confidence threshold for auto-proposal; matching customers to sold-to/ship-to; detect duplicates or conflicts with existing orders.  
- Outputs: Proposed “Order Draft” payload into Side-Car with confidence scores and source transcript links; flags for exceptions (e.g., missing FSSAI or export docs).  
- Escalation Triggers: Confidence below threshold; ambiguous sold-to/ship-to; pricing inconsistencies; ATP/credit failures—route to CSR. {DOC1, GB pricing/ATP gaps; India FSSAI; China ZF block preferences, paraphrase}

2) Order Change Advisor (Agent)  
- Responsibilities: Read customer change emails globally; locate target order(s); assess feasibility (ATP, credit/delivery block, pricing impact), simulate outcomes, and propose changes compliant with policy.  
- Inputs: Customer emails/attachments; Side-Car lookups; S/4 order data (read-only). {DOC1, APAC-ANZ, “All changes… processed manually in SAP based on email”; DOC2, intake/change handling, paraphrase}  
- Decisions: Apply change vs escalate; partial vs full change; propose new delivery date or split.  
- Outputs: Change Proposal record to Side-Car; if approved, Side-Car invokes standard APIs for S/4 update; acknowledgement email content prepared.  
- Escalation Triggers: Pricing discrepancies (GB gap), insufficient availability (ANZ ATP gap), blocked account/credit issues (India default block). {DOC1, GB/ANZ/India, paraphrase}

3) Export & Compliance Copilot (Agent)  
- Responsibilities: Analyze export orders and associated documentation; verify Incoterms/warehouse rule conformity; summarize compliance completeness and recommend delivery block (ZF) until satisfied.  
- Inputs: Attached docs, side-car business rules (required doc list by country/segment), order data. {DOC1, CALATIN/NA/China, “exports require extra documentation… Incoterms variations NA… ZF delivery blocks preferred,” paraphrase}  
- Decisions: Complete vs incomplete; apply/document block reason; request missing docs from customer.  
- Outputs: Compliance status summary to Side-Car; block/unblock recommendation; prepared customer request emails.  
- Escalation Triggers: Conflicting Incoterms/ship-to rules; incomplete mandatory docs; repeated non-compliance.

4) IDoc Sentinel & Reconciliation Analyst (Agent)  
- Responsibilities: Summarize failed IDocs, cluster by root cause, propose resolution actions (e.g., master data fix, retry); reconcile indirect orders with 3PL feeds (Vector) and Digital Hub postings.  
- Inputs: IDoc error logs; Side-Car event stream; Vector/Hub payloads. {DOC1, GB (WE05), SA (Vector), China (Digital Hub), paraphrase}  
- Decisions: Auto-retry vs route; assign to resolver groups; detect systemic patterns requiring upstream fix.  
- Outputs: Incident tickets with enriched context; retried IDoc submissions; reconciliation status dashboards.  
- Escalation Triggers: High failure rates; repeated errors for same partner/material; unreconciled orders after SLA.

Escalations always route to human roles (CSR/Export Specialist/IT EDI) via Side-Car work queues with full evidence. Clean Core: no agent writes directly into S/4; all updates occur via Side-Car invoking standard interfaces.

## 5) Technical Stack

- System of Record: SAP S/4HANA  
  - Role: Master data, pricing, ATP, credit/delivery blocks, sales orders/confirmations as official documents. Path A relies exclusively on configuration and standard capabilities (no custom code). {DOC1, gaps indicating need for ATP/pricing holds; e.g., ANZ/GB, paraphrase}
- Side-Car: SAP BTP orchestration/automation  
  - Role: Deterministic integration, channel normalization, validations, exception routing, acknowledgements, duplicate detection, cancellation logic, event monitoring, reconciliation, and region-specific integrations (Digital Hub, Vector, Power Street). All custom logic resides here to enforce Clean Core. {DOC1, China/SA/Uruguay/EMENA/JKSEAT, “Digital Hub… Vector… Power Street… off-time import… CSV/macro,” paraphrase}
- Agentic: SAP Joule/GenAI  
  - Role: Perception and reasoning for unstructured channels (email/WhatsApp/fax/web), change-request comprehension, export/deduction summarization—subject to confidence thresholds and human-in-loop until Autopilot maturity. {DOC1/DOC2, unstructured channels and manual change/dispute processing, paraphrase}

Not specified in inputs: names of specific BTP sub-services or API products; design remains technology-agnostic within BTP to comply with Clean Core and evidence rules.

## 6) The Trust Gap Protocol

We are currently at Shadow phase. We will operationalize Joule/GenAI agents and new automations through three phases with measurable gates:

- Shadow (Observe and Learn)  
  - Agents run in read-only, generating proposed extractions (orders/changes/compliance summaries) without action.  
  - Side-Car captures agent outputs, confidence scores, and ground truth from human processing to create labeled datasets.  
  - Metrics: extraction precision/recall (line-item level), duplicate detection accuracy, false-positive/false-negative rates, acknowledgement timeliness baseline, IDoc failure MTTR baseline. {Not specified in inputs—methodology detail; consistent with governance best practice}
- Co-Pilot (Human-in-the-Loop)  
  - Agents propose actions; humans approve/reject with reasons.  
  - Side-Car enforces gating: only proposals ≥ threshold (e.g., 0.9) are eligible for single-click approval. Lower confidence routes to manual completion with agent-provided context.  
  - Deterministic flows (Path B) move to production first; agentic flows remain co-piloted until metrics meet thresholds (e.g., ≥98% line-item accuracy for 60 days on a channel). {Not specified in inputs—operational thresholds; prudent governance}
- Autopilot (Guardrailed Autonomy)  
  - Agents execute within bounded policies for specific channels/partners where performance has stabilized.  
  - Audit: each autonomous action logs rationale, extracted fields, source references, and policy checks.  
  - Rollback: any anomaly triggers immediate fall-back to Co-Pilot for that partner/channel.

Promotion Gates (illustrative, to be finalized per region/channel):  
- Multi-Channel Comms Harvester: ≥98% extraction accuracy over N=1000 orders; duplicate prevention ≤0.1%; zero material price mismatch vs S/4 config for two consecutive months. {Not specified in inputs—example guardrails consistent with risk management}  
- Order Change Advisor: ≥99% correct mapping of change requests to orders; zero unauthorized changes; SLA improvements by ≥50% vs baseline.  
- Export & Compliance Copilot: ≥99% correct doc requirement checks; no compliance misses recorded.  
- IDoc Sentinel: ≥80% automated retries resolved without human for transient failures; time-to-detect ≤1 minute.

Clean Core remains intact in all phases: agents never embed logic in ERP; ERP remains authoritative for all controls and postings.

## 7) Risks, Guardrails, and Open Questions

Risks
- Over-automation of exceptions may propagate errors if controls (ATP/pricing/credit) are not first strengthened in S/4 (Path A). {DOC1, ANZ/GB/India, “ATP gap… no price validation… 100% credit block by default,” paraphrase}
- Dependence on single gateways (e.g., China Digital Hub) creates systemic risk; any outage stalls intake. {DOC1, APAC-CHINA, “All orders flow through Digital Hub,” paraphrase}
- Unstructured channel privacy/compliance (WhatsApp/email) across jurisdictions may restrict automated processing/storage. {DOC1, Brazil/Uruguay/Argentina/Mexico, “WhatsApp/email use for operations,” paraphrase}
- Brittle legacy automations (CSV macros, Excel EOD) pose transition risk during cutover if not phased or dual-run. {DOC1, JKSEAT/ANZ, “CSV macro… Excel macros EOD,” paraphrase}
- Regional variance (Brazil ECC exceptions, India DC model, Uruguay Power Street) complicates achieving global standardization timelines. {DOC1, Brazil/India/Uruguay, paraphrase}

Guardrails
- Clean Core enforcement: No custom logic in S/4 kernel; all non-standard behavior resides in BTP and is externally versioned and monitored. {Not specified in inputs—Clean Core principle stated in brief}
- Staged enablement: Path A controls must precede significant automation in Path B/C for affected regions. {DOC1, control gaps motivate sequencing, paraphrase}
- Dual-run for critical transitions (replace Excel EOD, CSV watchers, ZVA05N imports) with reconciliation reports until error rates are <0.1%. {DOC1, EMENA/ANZ/JKSEAT, “off-time import… Excel macros… CSV watchers,” paraphrase}
- Explainability and audit: Every agentic action retains source artifacts and machine-rationale; every deterministic automation logs decision rules and input data.
- Policy boundaries:  
  - Auto-cancellation only where policy allows (extend China logic case-by-case). {DOC1, APAC-CHINA, “Auto-cancellation logic Y1/Y5,” paraphrase}  
  - Delivery vs credit block enforcement aligned with regional finance controls (e.g., China ZF preference; India default block reconsideration). {DOC1, China/India, paraphrase}

Open Questions
- Volumes and exception frequencies: Quantify per region/channel to prioritize automation waves (e.g., NA exception frequency for new SKUs; ANZ duplicate EDI rates). {DOC1, multiple items with “Not specified,” e.g., P-001/P-026}
- Criteria for automatic vs manual acknowledgements by customer/segment; standardize SLA targets. {DOC1, Mexico/India/GB, “acknowledgement practices vary,” paraphrase}
- Detailed export documentation lists per country/segment to configure BTP gating and Export Copilot templates. {DOC1, CALATIN, “Exports require extra documentation,” paraphrase}
- Digital Hub roles: Who enters data (customer vs internal) and feasibility of API-based submissions to eliminate rekeying (China). {DOC1, APAC-CHINA, “Orders are manually entered… Not specified who enters,” paraphrase}
- Governance for capturing WhatsApp/email decisions into SAP: retention, consent, and regional legal constraints. {DOC1, Brazil/Uruguay/Argentina/Mexico, “WhatsApp/email… governance Not specified,” paraphrase}
- India DC governance standard work: process controls and readiness to centralize into Side-Car forms. {DOC1, APAC-INDIA, “Decentralized model… standard work Not specified,” paraphrase}
- Z7 CSR hold decommission plan: identify downstream dependencies and replace with standard configuration gates. {DOC1, APAC-ANZ, “Z7 CSR universal application,” paraphrase}
- EMENA ZVA05N retirement: identify S/4 standard equivalent integration and cutover sequence. {DOC1, EMENA, “ZVA05N only in EMENA,” paraphrase}

—

Implementation Roadmap (high level, aligned to Paths and Trust Gap)
- Wave 1 (Foundation-first):  
  - Path A: ATP and pricing gate deployment (ANZ/GB first), credit/delivery policy alignment (India/China), EDI entry normalization (ANZ), ZVA05N retirement plan (EMENA). {DOC1, ANZ/GB/India/China/EMENA, paraphrase}  
  - Path B: Replace Excel EOD and CSV watchers (ANZ/JKSEAT/Italy/NA), IDoc event monitoring baseline (GB/global), acknowledgements automation (GB/India/NA). {DOC1, ANZ/JKSEAT/GB/India/Italy/NA, paraphrase}  
  - Trust Gap: Agents in Shadow to collect data on email/WhatsApp/fax orders and changes.
- Wave 2 (Bridge and Co-Pilot):  
  - Path B: Digital Hub API orchestration (China), Power Street normalization (Uruguay), Vector reconciliation (SA), export/Incoterms rules (NA/CALATIN/India). {DOC1, China/Uruguay/SA/NA/CALATIN/India, paraphrase}  
  - Path C: Promote Comms Harvester and Order Change Advisor to Co-Pilot for top 3 channels by volume with human-in-the-loop approvals.
- Wave 3 (Autopilot domains):  
  - Path C: Autopilot for stable partners/channels meeting performance gates; Deduction Synthesizer deployment to reduce dispute cycle times. {DOC1, global deduction motif, paraphrase}

Every recommendation above directly addresses documented pain points and regional practices while upholding Clean Core: S/4 for standard controls; Side-Car for all custom orchestration; Joule/GenAI for unstructured intent where deterministic rules are insufficient.

